This is useful to prevent users fill in their form from the start when an error has occurred. To maintain form data after the submission action, save the form data to the session named `form`:

~~~ .php
if ($files = HTTP::files('blob')) {
    if (!empty($files['error'])) {
        // Store all form data to session
        Session::set('form', HTTP::post());
    } else {
        // Clear all form session on success
        Session::reset('form');
    }
}
~~~

The following is an example of generic HTML form markup:

~~~ .html
<form method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data">
  <p>
    <input name="image" type="file">
  </p>
  <p>
    <!-- These two fields will have persistent form data. -->
    <input name="file[name]" type="text">
    <input name="file[x]" type="text">
  </p>
  <p>
    <button type="submit">Upload</button>
  </p>
</form>
~~~